Feature: MoviesVC monochrome redesign based on image0 (UIKit)

Overview
- Redesign `MoviesVC` visual layout using `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/prototypes/movies-redesign2.prototype.html` as the primary visual target, derived from `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/image0.png`.
- Use monochrome palette only (black/white/gray).
- Add favoriting interaction for each movie card/row.
- Display ratings sourced from a mocked external API fixture.
- Remove footer navigation from this screen.

Scope
- In scope: `MoviesVC` layout refresh, mocked ratings presentation, favorite toggle UI/state, no footer navigation in MoviesVC, category chips fed from backend movie payload when available with iOS static fallback values.
- Out of scope: real external ratings integration, SwiftUI migration.

Functional requirements

REQ-MVC-RD-1 Design baseline from reference
- MoviesVC layout must follow the information hierarchy and structure direction of `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/prototypes/movies-redesign2.prototype.html`.
- `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/image0.png` remains the upstream inspiration source.
- Final implementation may adapt spacing and sizing for UIKit constraints and device classes.

REQ-MVC-RD-2 Monochrome theme
- MoviesVC uses a monochrome visual language: black, white, and gray tones only.
- No accent colors for primary UI surfaces, controls, or typography in this feature.

REQ-MVC-RD-2A Screen background and colors
- Screen background: white (#FFFFFF).
- Navigation buttons (Back): black (#000000), left-aligned.
- All other interactive buttons (favorites, category chips, CTA): grayscale only (black, white, gray range).
- Text rendering: use NSAttributedString for all labels, supporting configurable font family + size.

REQ-MVC-RD-2B Icon requirements
- Favorite toggle icon: heart (outline ☆ unfavorited, filled ★ favorited) or star equivalent; 32x32px, monochrome.
- Category chip icons: none required (text-only chips).
- Navigation: existing back button remains as text "Back" in black pill.
- Placeholder for missing movie poster: film reel icon or placeholder gradient; 52x52px rounded.

REQ-MVC-RD-3 Favorites capability
- Each movie item exposes a favorite toggle control.
- Favorite state must be visible in both selected and unselected states.
- Favorite interaction must be local and non-blocking.

REQ-MVC-RD-4 External ratings (mocked)
- Ratings are displayed for each movie using mocked external API data.
- Mock source must be a static JSON fixture bundled in app resources.
- If a rating is unavailable in fixture, UI shows a neutral fallback label (e.g., `N/A`).

REQ-MVC-RD-5 No footer navigation
- MoviesVC must not render footer navigation controls.
- Existing navigation flows to/from MoviesVC remain unchanged outside footer removal.

REQ-MVC-RD-5A Search bar retained
- Existing MoviesVC search bar must remain available for movie search interactions.
- Search behavior and existing search entry flow must remain functional after redesign.

REQ-MVC-RD-5B Segmented control removal
- Existing segmented control in MoviesVC must be removed from the redesigned screen.
- Segmented-control-based category switching is replaced by category chips from design.

REQ-MVC-RD-5C Categories from backend baseline with iOS fallback
- Available categories must be displayed as per `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/prototypes/movies-redesign2.prototype.html`.
- Backend remains the source of truth. If category values are missing from current backend responses, iOS must use static fallback chip values.
- Missing category data must not block movie rendering or interaction.

REQ-MVC-RD-6 List/grid content presentation
- Movie title remains visible and readable in monochrome mode.
- Rating and favorite indicator must be visible without requiring secondary navigation.

REQ-MVC-RD-7 Loading and error handling for ratings fixture
- Ratings fixture load failures must not block movie list rendering.
- On fixture read/parse failure, movies render with fallback rating display.

REQ-MVC-RD-8 UIKit-only constraint
- Feature implementation must use UIKit components only.
- Do not introduce SwiftUI views, wrappers, or hosting controllers for this scope.

REQ-MVC-RD-9 Logging and diagnostics
- Log fixture load success/failure and mapped rating count.
- Do not log sensitive headers, auth tokens, or secrets.

Non-functional requirements

REQ-MVC-RD-NF-1 Readability
- Contrast and typography must remain readable under monochrome styling.

REQ-MVC-RD-NF-2 Deterministic mapping
- Ratings from fixture must map deterministically by agreed movie key (e.g., movieId).

REQ-MVC-RD-NF-3 Performance
- Ratings hydration from local fixture should not introduce visible UI jank in MoviesVC.

Acceptance criteria
- [ ] MoviesVC visual redesign aligns to `movies-redesign2.prototype.html` (derived from `image0.png`) information hierarchy.
- [ ] UI uses monochrome palette only.
- [ ] Existing search bar remains present and usable in MoviesVC.
- [ ] Segmented control is removed from MoviesVC.
- [ ] Category chips are rendered as per design using backend-provided values when available, otherwise iOS static fallback values.
- [ ] Favorite toggle exists and state is visible per movie.
- [ ] Ratings are shown from static JSON fixture mock.
- [ ] Missing ratings show fallback (`N/A`) without blocking list.
- [ ] Footer navigation is absent from MoviesVC.
- [ ] UIKit-only implementation (no SwiftUI).
- [ ] Prototype document is attached for review.

Known issue / deferred hardening (FIX LATER)
- Current legacy path contains `category_!` force-unwrap risk before first category selection in section 1 (primary repro: `SwiftCinemas/SwiftLoginScreen/MoviesVC.swift:254`).
- This redesign scope tracks the issue as deferred safety hardening backlog and does not change runtime behavior in this spec phase.
- Backlog references:
  - `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/speckit.swiftuifeatures.moviesvc-redesign.tasks` (Phase 10)
  - `.specify/features/SwiftUIFeatures/speckit.swiftuifeatures.moviesvc-safety.analyze.md`

